      "FacilityID": 1000013640,
      "SummaryText": "1.  POLICIES\n     --------------\n     \nA.  An accidental release of a regulated substance would be detected by strategically-located VOC monitors that would immediately alert production personnel.  All drums and cylinders are leakproof-tested after filling;  all canisters are leak-tested each day of operation.  All tankcars are physically disconnected, valved-off, and capped during off-hours.  Security fencing, cameras, and alarms exist throughout the entire production facility.\n\nB.  An Emergency Action Plan has been prepared and submitted to the Colleton County Fire & Rescue Department and the LEPC specifying a response and warning system in the event of an accidental release of a regulated substance.  The facility also conducts quarterly evacuation drills according to the Emergency Action Plan.\n\n2.  STATIONARY SOURCE AND REGULATED SUBSTANCES\n     -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------\n\nA.  The primary activity is the repackaging of chemicals into drums, cylinders, and canisters for medical sterilization businesses and for synthesis customers.\n\nB.  The regulated substances are: \n           - Ethylene Oxide  \n           - Propylene Oxide   \n          \n3.  RELEASE SCENARIO\n     --------------------------------\n\nRemoved for site security.\n\n4.  PREVENTION\n     --------------------\n\nA.  All two regulated substances at the Green Pond plant are covered by the OSHA Process Safety Management (PSM) Standard.\n\n5.  FIVE-YEAR ACCIDENT HISTORY\n     ------------------------------------------------\n\nA.  There have been no accidental releases of any regulated substance during the past five years.\n\n6.  EMERGENCY RESPONSE PROGRAM\n     ---------------------------------------------------------\n\nA.  Evacuation drills have been conducted quarterly since 1997.  An evaluation of each drill is completed and changes are made based on the findings.\n\nB.  Walkie-talkies are used as a communication device in case of an emergency.\n\n7.  PLANNED CHANGE"
    },
